text: Good evening all hope you all had a great x mas and a happy new year to you all . Just after a bit of information if at all possible. I'm wondering how many of you adorable maine coon owners have had any health issues with your fur babies? The reason I ask as that I've seen a few post with hip operations but I also read that other possible health issues could include hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, hip dysplasia and spinal muscular atrophy. Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is the most common I hear. I currently own a grey tabby moggie of approx 17 months and our British shorthair of 12 weeks both adorable and were finishing off with a must have black smoke male maine coon. He's currently approx 7 weeks old and due to pick him up mid February. Can't wait! . The breeder states both parents are health checked but is there anything else we could do to try and prevent any health issues? I look forward to your knowledge and hopefully positive feedback. Here is a pic of our current cats and then a recent one of our black smoke üòä üòª üòª

text: Please no negative comments. I‚Äôm looking for advice. We have been using a Pet Safe electric fence for a few months now, and it has seemed to work well up until a week or so ago. Please understand that we only have a small fenced in area.  The fence gave my dog freedom in the yard and was working fine.  Now, he has broken through the boundary more than once to chase after a dog. It was a different dog each time. We live in a suburban neighborhood and people walk and walk dogs often.  Normally it is not an issue. I noticed with both occurrences his hair was raised on his back. He is a 10 month old male.  We have had him since he was 8 weeks old. Our plan was to take him to puppy classes once he had all his vaccinations. Unfortunately, he was diagnosed with giardia which took a couple rounds of meds to get rid of. We then started a class that was too basic since we already started working with him at home using videos for guidance.  He knows all the basics. But, when he took off both times, he did not care that I commanded him to stay.  We are currently working with a private trainer. He has not been neutered yet and I don‚Äôt plan on doing that until he is at least 12 months old. Has anyone struggled with these issues. I‚Äôm open to suggestions.

text: We had an absolutely terrifying experience this morning. Warning, LONG post. I've always been of the mind to leave my dogs collars off unless we were leaving our house or property. My husband disagreed with this very much. He was afraid if they got out of the yard. Both Goldens are chipped, so I've never worried, plus neither are runners. Our front door could be wide open and they wouldn't go anywhere. I went along with hubby's wishes and put their collars on when they're in the yard. It almost killed our youngest this morning! They were playing and Dio-gees tooth got stuck in Rebas collar! I don't know how long it went on, I had almost left for work when I heard her cries. I ran outside and she was on the ground in an extremely unnatural position with Dio-gee standing over her and his mouth on her neck. I thought they were fighting, which they never do, but they do play rough together. I didn't realize what was going on until I tried to pry his mouth open. Reba wasn't making any noise by that time. Their collars are breakaway, but hers was stuck. It probably took about 15-20 seconds for me to get the collar to release, but it seemed like an hour! She wasn't breathing at that point. I was screaming for help and screaming her name!  Out of absolute frustration, I screamed her name and hit her on the side! She started breathing again and opened her eyes! She still wasn't moving though and now Dio-gee was pacing around her whining and crying. I managed to get him in the house and scream upstairs that I needed help outside. Hubby and kids came running! She still wasn't moving or making any noise. I tried to pick her up to get her to the car and couldn't. I set her back down and she stayed in a sitting position. While we were trying to decide how to get her to the car without hurting her, my husband called her name and she got up and started walking! She was a bit wobbly at first, but is absolutely fine now! We are all still sick to our stomachs that this happened and both dogs are a little needy right now. Dio-gee won't let Reba out of his sight and whines if I stop petting her. I'm sharing this in hopes that no one else ever has go through what we did. It was a freak accident, but if the circumstances hadn't worked out exactly as they had, she wouldn't have survived! text: Seeing the vet soon, but we are really struggling with helping our girl, Katie. She has severe arthritis in her hind legs and cannot get up off the wooden floors or hard surfaces. So we‚Äôve tried traction shoes, sticky socks, and now adhesive pads to help her have traction. The sticky pads help but they don‚Äôt stay on long. And now it looks like they are damaging her paw pads plus I found her skin is really irritated between the toes. Suggestions greatly appreciated. By the way, her vet also tried 2 rounds of injections to ease the pain of arthritis but they did not help at all. We have yoga mats all over the house trying to help her and I‚Äôve now injured my back lifting her over and over. We cannot fathom putting her down as she‚Äôs only 10. text: Hi everyone, My 2 year old golden retriever is acting very down, not lethargic. Last night he had the runs, and then this morning ate half his meal and refused his supper. We had an issue last month with similar but worse behaviour, where he was feeling down, not eating, pooping but drinking water. Last time we assumed he ate something as he has done this a couple times. He is monitored closely and crated when we are away. When we took him to the vet his mood lifted but we tested him for several issues anyways. It turned out he had a liver infection and may have had a UTI. Meds and gastro food for the next week helped bring him back to normal. We are going to monitor him until tomorrow and then determine if we are taking him back to the vet. Any one had this happen before? What could it be? More liver tests? I‚Äôd like to have some sort of direction or idea before we go back to the vet so we don‚Äôt aimlessly run tests and another large vet bill. Thanks, Caroline and her golden, Reggie.  https://scontent-cdg4-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/415604520_10163397459114968_3732745689218613804_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_p526x296&_nc_cat=110&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=_ZUecsENqP8AX9Yu30R&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-1.xx&oh=00_AfDPHJRKKJTnGGg2tPHikrC6eezOt7cPhCq6OpggsMBYYA&oe=659E22B6

text: I feel I must give a good recommendation to Healthy Paws Pet Insurance. They advertise paying 80% of covered expenses. They don't pay for exams, inoculations, pre-existing conditions, or special food, but most everything else, including x-rays, sonograms, and CT scans. Sadly, Clancy only survived a week in ICU critical care after his hemangiosarcoma surgery. The hospital bill was over $17,000. Healthy Paws just paid me $14,100. It's really easy to file claims and upload supporting documents. I already have a policy for Cade with them!  https://scontent-cdg4-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/416905265_10232951348594223_2025085026863827283_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_p526x296&_nc_cat=105&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=idoRhqlTZfwAX_hQoWX&_nc_oc=AQlgY8VkltX1ILvsqDmgMHI2QbaEfHxvghLfwDBKBFajppah3kag5jsUwHsOGuXL66iFkqXBuJHDTZpPSh5DjgL2&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-1.xx&oh=00_AfC0XWrxWtOUifjeVAaVGRF9REdUKArT5PcfOfDcO78Rpg&oe=659DF012

text: My 6 yr old (just turned 6 Dec 27th) golden Storm was just diagnosed with intermediate-large cell lymphoma. Currently waiting on PCR test results to find out what type it is and schedule appt with Oncologist.All her lymph nodes are swollen the size of golf balls. Has not spread internally so we caught it in early stages. She is starting to have slight difficulty swallowing her dry kibble. We are going to start cooking her food at home. She has chicken allergy so we will be using ground turkey, lamb and beef liver. ( she hates fish/salmon). Brown rice,oatmeal,carrots, green veggies,blueberries,apples.I just need some guidance/reassurance with anyone‚Äôs personal experience going through something similar with their babies. Already ordered multivitamins,digestive enzymes,calcium powder and turkey tail supplements. Am I missing anything? I just want to help her the best we can.
author: Bridgit Moran

text: *****Advice***** Our shadow girl just turned 9. She's been through a lot in the last year with a major surgery and an infection. About a year and a half ago she had 2 seizures. About 6 months later She had another too. The vet said they wouldn't recommend putting her on medication because they weren't super frequent and so spaced out. While at work on New Year's Eve I found out that she had a small one and then a really bad 10 minutes after. Thinking it had been 6 months since her last 2 I figured we'd be in the clear. Unfortunately I woke up at 7 AM About an hour ago to her having another one it wasn't bad and she came out of it within 2 minutes. It was the kind where she was stiff but not shaking like crazy I was able to calmly talk her out of it and she immediately started acting like a puppy. I will be getting her into the next week if there's an appointment available. The advice I'm asking is for other golden parents that have anything like this going on what kind of medication or things do you use that you have noticed a significant difference or has helped. And does anybody else having these type of issues. Wondering if anybody has used CBD oils or drops to help calm them down when this happens.  https://scontent-cdg4-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/417004239_10224676536442816_3509269999207911111_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_s1080x2048&_nc_cat=110&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=NC46bRvKA-kAX-IJlr6&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-1.xx&oh=00_AfAZQ7tWt49lkByuHuBr0MIAOyMxW3fFWJNqx4hqnIZYkg&oe=659ED18D

text: This is Story of a Golden Retriever that may be harboring a secret identity... I have frequently posted about Bo,our bestest boy , and his pack mates, Cammie the Lab, Rusty Jones, and Coco. Last night, late, all was quiet as I got ready to jump in the shower. Then came this noise...a howl, much more than that really, the most prolonged ,from the depths of hell howl that literally sent chills down my spine! I ran to the living room and said to my hubby "WHAT WAS THAT????" He said "Bo". Bo was sound asleep like nothing had happened, but I was shook. Tom ( hubby) said if the lights had been off, he would have **** himself. I told him what I had heard was Hounds of Hell, Werewolf shit!!!!!!! Bo has never howled in the 4 years we've had him. I checked for a full moon, cause I'm on to Bo now. I finished getting ready for bed, went through the kitchen, grabbed a head of garlic, and offered a few cloves to my husband, just in case. I realize now that garlic is geared more towards Vampires, but I wasn't taking any chances. Good Night everybody, I said. If you need me, just yell. It will take me a minute to unlock the door and push the dresser out of the way to get to you, but I'll come.  https://scontent-cdg4-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/415503741_3664053943842361_8000562139503550533_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_p526x296&_nc_cat=108&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=ziUSIHiubWMAX857Pen&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-1.xx&oh=00_AfCkBFzl7tuIGPHqfO5qwrpUig8I75B3EkNp7Bhf7OgRBQ&oe=659F77FE

text: The Daily Dolly. The ongoing tale of our beautiful rescue Goldie, HRH Princess Dolly Lazar.  Our poor little Princess was not very well yesterday.  It started on Sunday night - she kept drinking lots of water and then retching.  She had us up several times that night to go outside where she kept trying to be sick but was only producing clear/frothy liquid.  She rather gingerly ate some breakfast yesterday and seemed OK on her walk but then was very lethargic and continued to drink lots of water, after which she would try to be sick.  We were concerned it might be bloat but her stomach did not feel at all distended, her gums were not pale and she did not appear to be in pain.  Of course being New Year's Day the vet was closed so we decided to monitor her and get her to an emergency vet if necessary.  She remained very listless all day and Dylan was so sweet and gentle with her, lying beside her most of the day and not trying to indulge in any rough and tumble - such a good and sensitive pup!  I made her some scrambled egg and whole grain rice in the evening which she enjoyed and I'm pleased to say kept down.  She slept through the night and enjoyed some more egg and rice for breakfast and now seems OK.  Fingers crossed! Such a worry when they are ill!  https://scontent-cdg4-2.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t39.30808-6/413002756_6820152908082942_4438047568167804008_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_p180x540&_nc_cat=103&ccb=1-7&_nc_sid=c42490&_nc_ohc=jVGnqgHK1VoAX-R3dRc&_nc_ht=scontent-cdg4-2.xx&oh=00_AfDwuInlQ4eyt4zxqSbqTPIWo-4Y82mScuyuXwPbFiE3KA&oe=659FC82A

text: One may ask why is your one year old golden so tired??  The answer is because he has taken on a very very big job! My daughter has had health issues since birth(now 24) we recently found out she needs a double organ transplant(liver and pancreas)! Well Oliver has taken on the role of protector and  blood sugar inspector through the night, (he has not been trained he is our pet). Somehow Oliver knows when Kylie Giel is in trouble and he will relentlessly try to wake me up and forces his way into her bedroom when her sugar is unstable, he will paw, whine, and bite her hand until she is up and addressing whatever issue is going on! Some may not believe our story but this isn‚Äôt the first time! Oliver has been acting strangely around kylie since September when her health nightmare started. He has always spent the night in our bedroom since he came home but starting in September he now goes in Kylie‚Äôs bedroom until she is up for the day when no one else is home. Oliver will not leave Kylie‚Äôs bed until she does! Dogs are a gift and angels on earth! So thankful for this guy! He has a rough job but he is amazing at it!!!
